'''Ross Cameron Stewart''' (born 11 July 1996) is a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[forward (association football)|forward]] for {{English football updater|Southamp}} club [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].

He began his career with [[Ardeer Thistle F.C.|Ardeer Thistle]] and [[Kilwinning Rangers F.C.|Kilwinning Rangers]] before joining [[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]] in 2016. After one season, Stewart moved to [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] and went on loan to [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]]. In 2018, he joined [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]], spending three seasons with the club before joining [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in 2021 and helping them win promotion to the Championship. Stewart then signed for Southampton in 2023.

==Club career==
===Junior League===
After spells with the youth systems of professional clubs,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60158844 |title=Ross Stewart: Sunderland striker caps rise from juniors with Scotland call-up|work=BBC Sport|date=21 March 2022}}</ref> Stewart started his career in the [[Scottish Junior Football Association|Scottish Juniors]] with [[Ardeer Thistle F.C.|Ardeer Thistle]] and [[Kilwinning Rangers F.C.|Kilwinning Rangers]],<ref name = juniors>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/clypkxye9w2o |title=Ross Stewart: Southampton striker's rise from Scottish juniors to World Cup |website=BBC Sport |first1=Martin |last1=Watt |first2=Nick |last2=McPheat |date=19 May 2026 |accessdate=19 May 2026}}</ref> before making the step-up to senior football with [[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]] in July 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |date=18 July 2016 |title=Ross Stewart to sign for Rovers |work=albionroversfc.co.uk |url=http://albionroversfc.co.uk/ross-stewart-to-sign-for-rovers/ |access-date=7 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722231741/http://albionroversfc.co.uk/ross-stewart-to-sign-for-rovers/ |archive-date=22 July 2016}}</ref> The part-time [[Coatbridge]] club were unable to pay the £1,500 transfer fee, with the funds instead provided by their supporters' club members and by Stewart's father.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/local-sport/ross-stewarts-kilwinning-rangers-albion-22762274.amp|title=Ross Stewart's Kilwinning Rangers to Albion Rovers transfer paid by his dad to give him SPFL shot|work=Daily Record|date=1 October 2020}}</ref>

===St Mirren===
After just one season with Albion Rovers, Stewart signed for [[Scottish Championship]] club [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] on a two-year full-time contract (a [[Ross Stewart (footballer, born 1995)|goalkeeper with the same name]] also joined at the time).<ref>{{Cite news |date=26 May 2017 |title=St Mirren: Two Ross Stewarts sign for Buddies from Albion Rovers |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40067934 |access-date=7 January 2018}}</ref> Stewart scored on his debut for the [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]] club in a [[Scottish League Cup]] win versus [[Stranraer F.C.|Stranraer]]<ref>{{Cite news |date=15 July 2017 |title=Stranraer 1-4 St Mirren match report |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40619985 |access-date=8 January 2018}}</ref> but failed to break into the first-team and was loaned out to [[Scottish League One]] club [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]] in December 2017, for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|date=21 December 2017 |title=Ross Stewart joins Alloa Athletic on loan |url=https://www.stmirren.com/news/club/all-news/1414-ross-to-join-alloa-athletic-on-loan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811032602/https://www.stmirren.com/news/club/all-news/1414-ross-to-join-alloa-athletic-on-loan |archive-date=11 August 2018 |access-date=8 January 2018 |work=stmirren.com}}</ref>

===Ross County===
On 10 August 2018, Stewart signed for [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=10 August 2018 |title=Ross County confirm signing of St Mirren striker Ross Stewart |work=Press and Journal |url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/sport/1538705/ross-county-confirm-signing-of-st-mirren-striker-ross-stewart/ |access-date=10 August 2018}}</ref> He made his debut for the club in a 2–1 victory in the [[Scottish Challenge Cup]] against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Heart of Midlothian Colts]]. Stewart scored his first goal for the club in the next round of the cup in a win against [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]]. He finished his first season at Ross County with 11 goals, three of them coming against County's Rivals [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]] as Ross County were promoted to the [[Scottish Premiership]].

===Sunderland===
On 31 January 2021, Stewart joined English side [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stewart departs Staggies |url=https://www.rosscountyfootballclub.co.uk/news-items/stewart-departs-staggies |publisher=Ross County FC - Official Site |access-date=31 January 2021}}</ref> Stewart scored on his Sunderland debut after coming on as a substitute against [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] in a 2–0 away win on 17 March 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55406658 |title=Accrington Stanley 0-2 Sunderland |website=BBC Sport |date=17 March 2021 |access-date=18 March 2021}}</ref> He was later given the nickname '[[Loch Ness]] Drogba' by Sunderland supporters in reference to his Scottish heritage and comparisons with prolific former [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] striker [[Didier Drogba]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/19545043.ross-stewart-discusses-loch-ness-drogba-nickname/ |title=Ross Stewart discusses his 'Loch Ness Drogba' nickname |last=Wilson |first=Scott |date=30 August 2021 |work=[[Sunderland Echo]] |access-date=30 May 2022 }}</ref>

On 21 May 2022, Stewart scored the second goal in the [[2022 EFL League One play-off final]] as Sunderland defeated [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] 2–0 to gain promotion back to the [[EFL Championship]]. He finished the season as the league's joint top goalscorer with 26 goals and was later voted the [[PFA Fans' Player of the Year]] for League One.<ref name="PFAFans" />

During a 1–1 draw with [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on 28 January 2023 in the [[FA Cup]] fourth round, he was forced off in the first half after suffering an achilles injury.<ref>{{Cite web |date=28 January 2023 |title=Ross Stewart: Sunderland striker's Achilles injury 'bad', says Tony Mowbray |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64440288 |access-date=1 December 2023 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> A week later, it was confirmed that Stewart would miss the remainder of the [[2022–23 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2022–23]] season.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2 February 2023 |title=Ross Stewart: Sunderland striker out for season after Achilles injury |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64499534 |access-date=1 December 2023 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

=== Southampton ===
On 1 September 2023, Stewart joined [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] on a three-year contract for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{Cite web |date=1 September 2023 |title=Saints swoop for Sunderland striker Stewart |url=https://www.southamptonfc.com/en/news/article/saints-swoop-for-sunderland-striker-stewart |access-date=2 September 2023 |website=Southampton FC}}</ref> He made his debut for the club on 11 November 2023 in a 2–1 victory against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]], replacing [[Adam Armstrong (footballer)|Adam Armstrong]] in the 83rd minute.<ref>{{Cite web |date=11 November 2023 |title=Southampton 2–1 West Bromwich Albion |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67318251 |access-date=11 November 2023 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> During Southampton's 1–1 draw with [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] on 25 November 2023, Stewart picked up an injury, with manager [[Russell Martin (footballer)|Russell Martin]] later confirming he was expected to be sidelined until late January.<ref>{{Cite web |date=1 December 2023 |title=Stewart and Kamaldeen set for spell on the sidelines |url=https://www.southamptonfc.com/en/news/article/stewart-and-kamaldeen-set-for-spell-on-the-sidelines |access-date=1 December 2023 |publisher=Southampton F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=House |first=Alfie |date=1 December 2023 |title=Southampton's Stewart and Kamaldeen sidelined until the New Year |url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/sport/23962244.southamptons-stewart-kamaldeen-sidelined-new-year/ |access-date=1 December 2023 |website=Southern Daily Echo}}</ref> On 22 December 2023, it was confirmed that the injury to his hamstring would rule Stewart out for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stewart unlikely to feature again this season |url=https://www.southamptonfc.com/en/news/article/stewart-unlikely-to-feature-again-this-season |access-date=23 December 2023 |publisher=Southampton F.C. |date=22 December 2023}}</ref> Stewart returned from injury in a 2–1 away victory against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] on the final day of the [[2023–24 Southampton F.C. season|2023–24]] season, replacing Adam Armstrong in the 83rd minute.<ref>{{Cite web |date=4 May 2024 |title=Stewart return delights Martin |url=https://www.southamptonfc.com/en/news/article/stewart-return-delights-martin |access-date=7 May 2024 |publisher=Southampton F.C.}}</ref>

On 14 September 2024, Stewart made his first [[Premier League]] appearance in a 3–0 home defeat against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] after he replaced [[Cameron Archer]] in the 62nd minute.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rose |first=Gary |date=14 September 2024 |title=Southampton 0–3 Manchester United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cn0ldr4n9n2t#Report |access-date=8 October 2024 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> During his first start for the club since his permanent transfer, on 5 October 2024, Stewart suffered a muscle injury in a 3–1 defeat against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=House |first=Alfie |date=5 October 2024 |title=Martin issues Stewart update as Southampton striker injured |url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/sport/24632601.martin-issues-stewart-update-southampton-striker-injured/ |access-date=8 October 2024 |website=Southern Daily Echo}}</ref> On 25 May 2025, he scored his first goal for the club in a 2–1 home defeat against Arsenal.<ref>{{Cite web |last=House |first=Alfie |date=25 May 2025 |title=Stewart scores first Southampton goal in late Arsenal win |url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/sport/25190186.stewart-scores-first-southampton-goal-late-arsenal-win/ |access-date=26 May 2025 |website=Southern Daily Echo}}</ref>

==International career==
Stewart received his first call-up to the senior [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] squad in March 2022 whilst playing for [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60813364 |title=Scotland: Sunderland striker Ross Stewart, Hearts defender Craig Halkett & St Johnstone keeper Zander Clark called up |date=21 March 2022 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=21 March 2022}}</ref> He made his international debut on 8 June 2022, appearing as a substitute in a [[2022–23 UEFA Nations League|Nations League]] game against [[Armenia national football team|Armenia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/sport/football/scottish/4394451/ross-stewart-says-scotland-debut-has-settled-him-into-national-team-setup/ |title=Ross Stewart says Scotland debut has settled him into national team setup |first=Andy |last=Skinner |newspaper=Press & Journal |date=9 June 2022 |access-date=10 June 2022}}</ref> 

Stewart was not selected by Scotland for four years, mainly due to injuries, but he was recalled to the squad by [[Steve Clarke]] for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026 World Cup finals]].<ref name = juniors/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c4g94rpvx73o |title=2026 World Cup: Scotland select Ross Stewart & Findlay Curtis in 26-man squad |website=BBC Sport |date=19 May 2026 |accessdate=19 May 2026}}</ref>

